    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Price of Stopping Terrorists</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Harvey W Kushner letter comments on problems that arise in trying to protect United States personnel against suicide missions or other terrorist attacks (Oct 17 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Terrorist Threat at Sea'' (editorial, Oct. 17):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Terrorist Threat at Sea'' (editorial, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>No amount of target-hardening and corresponding efforts to reduce dangers will protect United States personnel against suicide missions or other terrorist threats. The United States military can function only as an extension of a free and open society. To ask it to develop security protocols more repressive than operational directs an action that is anathema to the American experience.</p>
        <p>Along with our worldview and our presence in hostile foreign lands comes a price. Should the threat of terrorism outweigh the loss of freedom by moving our military forces further along a path that would have them institute measures approaching the militaries of some totalitarian regimes?</p>
        <p>HARVEY W. KUSHNER  Brookville, N.Y., Oct. 17, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of criminal justice and security administration at Long Island University.</p>
      </block>
